That's true, just `#add` would also do the trick. Most of the collections already have `#add` anyways. `#conj` is a nod to Clojure, and will be familiar to anyone who has programmed in Clojure. `#conjoin` is like `#conj` but a bit more verbose (and more readable to non-Clojure programmers).

`#add` is the most understandable of all to programmers who don't use Clojure.

@dubek, do you have any input?

@xbeta: This is intended. To quote from the README:

> Hamster collections are immutable. Whenever you modify a Hamster collection, the original is preserved and a modified copy is returned. This makes them inherently thread-safe and shareable. At the same time, they remain CPU and memory-efficient by sharing between copies. 

This is true for all Hamster's data structures: `Hamster::Hash`, `Hamster::Vector`, and so on. So a `#push` or a `#set` on a `Hamster::Vector` instance will return a new one, unlike Ruby's built-in `Array` which will modify the instance in-place.

@dubek thanks for the explanation, but what's stopping one thread `push()` and another thread `pop()` at the same time in a concurrency world?

``` ruby
def initialize()
  @nums = Hamster::Deque.new()
end
..
def add(num)
   # because hamster's deque is immutable
   @nums = @nums.push(num)
end
```

@krainboltgreene two other problem with `to_hash`:
- It's not a unified interface across all the Hamster collections—we would need `Hamster::Vector#to_a`, `Hamster::Set#to_set` (?).
- It may be expensive, depending on how deep the object is. I'm not sure what user expectations are on a method called `to_hash`.

The `json` module, however, mixes in `Object#to_json`. Maybe Hamster we can do `Hamster::Hash#to_mutable` (and the rest).

@alexdowad on top of the alternative above, what about `Hamster.to_mutable`.

